SIMPLE: popularity
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Popularity
<hw>Pop`u*lar"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Popularities</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L.
<ets>popularitas</ets> an effort to please the people: cf. F.
<ets>popularit⟦eacute⟧</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality or
state of being popular; especially, the state of being esteemed by, or
of being in favor with, the people at large; good will or favor
proceeding from the people; <as>as, the <ex>popularity</ex> of a law,
statesman, or a book</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>popularity</qex> which has lasted down to our time.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The quality or state of being adapted or pleasing to
common, poor, or vulgar people; hence, cheapness; inferiority;
vulgarity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This gallant laboring to avoid <qex>popularity</qex> falls into a
habit of affectation.</q> <rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Something which obtains, or is intended to obtain,
the favor of the vulgar; claptrap.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Popularities</qex>, and circumstances which . . . sway the
ordinary judgment.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The act of courting the favor of the people.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Indicted . . . for <xex>popularity</xex> and
ambition.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Holland.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Public sentiment; general passion.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A little time be allowed for the madness of <qex>popularity</qex>
to cease.</q> <rj><qau>Bancroft.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Popularization</ent>⟦br⟧
